      "finding": "The 'null model' is not a null model. The Monte Carlo samples triples that are constrained to exactly satisfy the Koide relation (Q=2/3). This conditions on the very phenomenon being investigated (the Koide relation for leptons) and then checks for a secondary coincidence. A true null model for assessing the rarity of the joint event (Koide + mass match) would sample triples from a distribution representing the 'null' of no special relation (e.g., random masses within physical ranges) and then apply both the Koide filter and the Soddy-quark check. The described procedure only estimates the conditional probability of the quark match GIVEN the Koide relation, which is not the relevant probability for assessing the overall surprise of the finding.",
